hands_on_practices.solution:
We are given the Pauli matrices
$$
\sigma_{x}=\begin{pmatrix}0&1\\\\1&0\end{pmatrix},\quad
\sigma_{y}=\begin{pmatrix}0&-i\\\\i&0\end{pmatrix},\quad
\sigma_{z}=\begin{pmatrix}1&0\\\\0&-1\end{pmatrix},
$$
and the operator $S=\sigma_{x}+\sigma_{y}$. The anti-commutator of two operators $A$ and $B$ is defined as $\{A,B\}=AB+BA$. We must compute $\{\sigma_{z},S\}$.

By linearity of the product and the definition of $S$, we have
$$
\{\sigma_{z},S\}=\sigma_{z}S+S\sigma_{z}
=\sigma_{z}(\sigma_{x}+\sigma_{y})+(\sigma_{x}+\sigma_{y})\sigma_{z}
=(\sigma_{z}\sigma_{x}+\sigma_{x}\sigma_{z})+(\sigma_{z}\sigma_{y}+\sigma_{y}\sigma_{z}).
$$
Equivalently, we can compute directly using matrices. First compute $S$:
$$
S=\sigma_{x}+\sigma_{y}
=\begin{pmatrix}0&1\\\\1&0\end{pmatrix}
+\begin{pmatrix}0&-i\\\\i&0\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}0&1-i\\\\1+i&0\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Next compute the products $\sigma_{z}S$ and $S\sigma_{z}$:
$$
\sigma_{z}S=\begin{pmatrix}1&0\\\\0&-1\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}0&1-i\\\\1+i&0\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}
1\cdot 0+0\cdot(1+i) & 1\cdot(1-i)+0\cdot 0\\\\
0\cdot 0+(-1)\cdot(1+i) & 0\cdot(1-i)+(-1)\cdot 0
\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}0&1-i\\\\-(1+i)&0\end{pmatrix},
$$
$$
S\sigma_{z}=\begin{pmatrix}0&1-i\\\\1+i&0\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}1&0\\\\0&-1\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}
0\cdot 1+(1-i)\cdot 0 & 0\cdot 0+(1-i)\cdot(-1)\\\\
(1+i)\cdot 1+0\cdot 0 & (1+i)\cdot 0+0\cdot(-1)
\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}0&-1+i\\\\1+i&0\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Adding these two matrices gives the anti-commutator:
$$
\{\sigma_{z},S\}=\sigma_{z}S+S\sigma_{z}
=\begin{pmatrix}0&1-i\\\\-(1+i)&0\end{pmatrix}
+\begin{pmatrix}0&-1+i\\\\1+i&0\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}0&0\\\\0&0\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Therefore, the anti-commutator is the zero $2\times 2$ matrix.
